<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>For Aphrodite, the gods Augusti, the People: Eusebes (entitled) lover of his country, and Menandros, the sons of Menandros the son of Eunkos and Apphias daughter of Menandros (set up) the Propylon, and the honorific statues on it.</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary" n="notyet">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>For the dedicators see <xref type="iAph">1278</xref> (=CIG 2738+) and <xref type="iAph">1928</xref> (=MAMA 489), and, specifically, the other Sebasteion texts: <xref type="iAph">1270</xref> (=81.85+) (the north portico); <xref type="iAph">1272</xref> (=81.182+) (an almost identical text, but fuller, from the propylon), and <xref type="iAph">1274</xref> (=83.54+), also from the propylon, referring to a restoration after earthquakes.</p><p>For discussion see Reynolds, loc. cit.</p>
</div>
